column1: 10232;DevNet (DEV);DEVNET-1016;Transforming Network Operations from Configuration Automation Through State Validation with Ansible;Please Note: By registering for this session
column2: it does not guarantee you a seat. Seating is available on a first come first seated basis.This talk will focus on the unique operational challenges facing organizations considering how to leverage the emerging trends of implementing agile practices to encompass the physical network infrastructure. It will focus on technical and cultural challenges facing organizations attempting to embrace this transition including how Ansible is uniquely architected to serve as the right foundational framework for powering this change. It will touch on why it's more important than ever for organizations to embrace the need to introduce new automated orchestration capabilities and start the process of moving away from traditional command and control network device administration being done hop by hop.  The presentation will demonstrate some of the theories in action and touch on expanding configuration automation to include elements of state validation of configuration changes.  Finally
column3: the discussion will also touch on the changing role of the network engineering and operations teams and why their expertise is needed now more than ever to lead this transition. column1: 10488;DevNet (DEV);DEVNET-1040;Devnet Workshop - Introduction to Python Network Programming for Network Architects and Engineers - Part 1: The Basics;"Please Note:  Seating for sessions in the DevNet Zone is available on a first come first seated basis.

This three part class introduces participants to two of the core building blocks of many automation initiatives – the Python programming language and network programming concepts. No previous programming background is required. The 3 sessions may be taken as a series or individually. See DEVNET-1041 and DEVNET-1042 for description of Parts 2 and 3.The goal in Part 1 is for participants to develop a set of Python “building block” templates that can be used as the foundation for more advanced topics. These templates include:o How to take input from the Python command line or from the keyboard (in the form of an arbitrary domain name).o How to leverage the Python socket library to retrieve the IP address of the Domain Name device.o How to leverage Python to save those Domain Name’s and IP addresses to a simple log file.o A demonstration of a simple UDP based client/server countdown timer application.
This session takes place in the DevNet Zone. ";DevNet;Approved;Network Transformation

10500;DevNet (DEV);DEVNET-1045;Securing PaaS and SaaS:  What Are Cisco and Our Partners Doing to Secure Your Hybrid Cloud?;"Please Note:   Seating for sessions in the DevNet Zone is available on a first come first seated basis.
Digitization and the IOE have created unprecedented growth opportunities for our customers
column2: partners
column3: and attackers. As users and devices continue to leverage cloud services at an alarming rate of consumption for both developers and application owners
column4: security continues to be the number one issue. If understood and managed properly
column5: hybrid cloud environments could be a more secure option. This panel will be discussing what Cisco and our partners are doing to help secure PaaS and SaaS environments for hybrid cloud. We will discuss what partners and customers have done to help manage security and risk in a hybrid cloud environment. During this session we will be discussing how security needs to be built into the entire application development life cycle and how leveraging Security-as-a-Service to accelerate deployments of applications and services without compromising risk to the business. We will also be discussing what innovations are happing within Cisco to protect data and defend against an increasing attack surface that spans from users/devices to the cloud.

column1: Targeted Attacks
column2: which the media refers to as APTs
column3: are threats that must be addressed by any organization requiring networked computers to do business. We will explore using pxGrid and other tools to break these APT style attack playbooks.

column1: Backgrounder: We obtained knowledge of these run book techniques from trusted advisors

column3: our security products in the field as well as our internal phishing awareness campaign. After studying these techniques we devised strategies to mitigate them. column1: 10324;DevNet (DEV);DEVNET-1693;Introduction to Achieving Perf and Scale On Large Clouds;"Please Note: Seating for sessions in the DevNet Zone is available on a first come first seated basis.
One of the most daunting tasks of operating an OpenStack cloud is to assess the performance and scale of the data plane and storage plane under load.
To give you an idea
column2: here are just a few examples of performance and scale requirements required for a performant cloud: Verify that 2 VMs located on different hosts and the same Neutron network can exchange packets close to a 10 Gbps line rate Verify that a rack of servers can support 100 HTTP servers servicing 100
column4: 000 HTTP requests per second with 99% of all requests serviced within 100 msec Find the latency distribution of IO operations performed by 100 VMs doing random reads on a Cinder (attached) volume at a rate of 200 IOPs each

column1: Such assessments are usually only performed by experts as they require the installation of the right set of tools combined with the proper methodology to run and orchestrate these tools in the cloud under test
column2: followed by the collection
column3: aggregation and publication of the test results. Because these tasks are highly interactive and manual
column4: it can take easily days of work to produce summarized results that are in turn difficult to repeat over time.

column1: In this talk we will present 2 open sourced tools developed and used by Cisco to tune the performance and scale of the Cisco OpenStack NFV Infrastructure. These tools help get past the afore mentioned barriers to entry by providing a fool-proof and fully automated way to measure VM-level performance and scale metrics for data plane and storage plane.
VMTP - Provides automated measurement of the data plane performance using various Neutron topologies.

KloudBuster - Provides automated measurement at massive scale of the data plane using HTTP traffic and of the storage scale using real storage access from a large number of VMs.  This session takes place in the DevNet Zone.  ";DevNet;Approved;Cloud
column2: Open Source;45 min;Automation

column1: 10300;DevNet (DEV);DEVNET-2051;Mobile Presence and Operational Analytics with Splunk and Meraki;Can you Splunk your Cisco Meraki data to analyze foot traffic? Let us show you how. Splunk extracts the relevant information from your network data using Meraki's Syslog function and enables Meraki customers to correlate this data with machine data across the infrastructure to for better operational intelligence. Splunk works with Cisco Meraki to help organizations gain insights leveraging the vast amounts of data generated by Meraki's MR wireless access points and MX security appliances. -Analyze foot traffic analytics -Determine wait times for customers -Collect Syslog data for network analytics -Download the app and install it on your own Splunk instance;DevNet;Approved;Analytics & Automation

column1: Cisco Open Plug-n-Play solution allows customers to reduce the costs associated with deployment/installation of network devices
column2: increase the speed and reduce the complexity of deployments without compromising the security. Using Cisco Plug-n-Play solution
column3: customers can do Zero Touch Installs of Cisco gear in various deployment scenarios and deployment locations. Plug-n-Play provides same user experience for routers
column5: and wireless access points whether they are being installed in a campus or branch or a data center. Cisco Open Plug-n-Play is based on industry standard protocols like DHCP
column7: HTTP/HTTPS
column9: and TCL/Python. Customers and partners have the ability to integrate with their existing tools and customize the installation process as required by their business processes. This session will focus on providing the following major topics:

column1: An in-depth overview of Cisco Open Plug-n-Play protocol
Go over various workflows for zero touch provision with Cisco Open Plug-n-Play
Hands on development of end-to-end provisioning workflows with Open Play-n-Play protocol

column1: This API Workbench takes a developer from understanding concepts of using REST and RAML (Restful API Modeling Language) to create usable APIs
column2: and publishing them onto portals with access control and poicy management. The advanced level of labs in a longer online series takes an API developer through the steps needed to automatically convert and expose their core/back-end APIs that have been written in a language like JAX-RS to RAML for exposure and notebook (composing) services.  This session takes place in the DevNet Zone.  ";DevNet;Approved;Application Development;45 min;Enterprise Application
